👉 Exception class in Java

We can write our custom Exceptions using Exception class in Java.

public class My Exception extends Exception{
    // override methods
}

The Exception class has following important methods :

1. String toString() -> executed when sout(e) is ran
2. void printStackTrace() -> prints stack trace
3. String getMessage() -> prints the exception message

Example Code :

import java.util.Scanner;

// Custom Exception Class
class MyException extends Exception {

    // Override toString() method
    @Override
    public String toString() {
        return "I am toString() method";
    }

    // Override getMessage() method
    @Override
    public String getMessage() {
        return "I am getMessage() method";
    }
}

public class ExceptionClass {
    public static void main(String[] args) {

        Scanner sc = new Scanner(System.in);

        System.out.print("Enter a number: ");
        int a = sc.nextInt();

        // Condition check
        if (a < 99) {
            try {
                // Throw custom exception
                throw new MyException();
            } catch (Exception e) {

                // Prints message from getMessage()
                System.out.println("Using getMessage(): " + e.getMessage());

                // Prints message from toString()
                System.out.println("Using toString(): " + e.toString());

                // Prints full error details (class + line number)
                System.out.println("Using printStackTrace():");
                e.printStackTrace();
            }
        } else {
            System.out.println("Number is valid (>= 99)");
        }

        sc.close();
    }
}

